                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. de Stoeckl</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                        Seward</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>,</placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1867-08-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 20, 1867</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. <hi rend="smallcaps">Secretary of State:</hi> In reply to the letter you have
                    done me the honor to address to me on the 15th of this month, I make it a duty
                    to inform <pb facs="0475" n="407" xml:id="pg_407"/> you that the only point at
                    which we had a military garrison was at Sitka. The number of men we maintained
                    there never exceeded two hundred, and latterly there were at Sitka only 80 men.
                    The barracks in which these troops are stationed, and which will be turned over
                    to the federal government, may conveniently hold from a hundred to a hundred and
                    twenty men. Besides the garrison at Sitka, there are some advanced posts on the
                    mainland, occupied by four or fi<hi rend="italic">ve</hi> men each. These posts
                    are situated far to the north, and it will be difficult to turn them over to the
                    United States troops before next spring. As to what relates to provisions, the
                    federal government will be able to supply itself in the warehouses of the
                    Russo-American Company with breadstuffs, butter, sugar, tea, and salt fish. In
                    the Sitka market may be found fresh fish, goat meat, wild, in small quantities.
                    It would be well for the American government to take measures for provisioning
                    its troops with fresh meat or salted, coffee, and other articles which are used
                    in the United States army.</p>
                <p>Please accept, Mr. Secretary of State, the assurance of my very high
                    consideration.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>STOECKL.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>Hon. <hi rend="smallcaps">William H. Seward</hi>, <hi rend="italic">&amp;c.,
                            &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
